An aging congress

Sam Johnson

2023-05-04

Introduction

This analysis will use data from fivethirtyeight.com on the demographics of congressmen in the 118th congress of the United states. One of the problems often mentioned is that this congress is far too old. Here we will be looking at various metrics of age across the two chambers of Congress, as well as individually. These metrics will be party affiliation, location, and time in chamber and congress. Older members of Congress will be defined as 65 or older. The entirety of the code used to produce this report will be include at the end.

Before entering into the specific questions that we can ask, lets look at some of the summary statistics for Congress age.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   26.00   49.00   59.00   58.56   68.00   90.00

1. Who are the oldest members of Congress?

It is unacceptable that anyone in their 90s should be running the country. Despite this, there is one, at least by rounded age, while the rest of the oldest members of Congress are all in their 80s. The names of these congressmen can be found below.

2. Which party dominates in terms of the oldest members of the Congress?

Democrats clearly win out in terms of elderly politicians in Congress, while Independents are actually the most likely to be elderly, there are only three. Republicans meanwhile make up about 3/4 the number of elderly Democrats in Congress.

## Warning: The dot-dot notation (`..count..`) was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `after_stat(count)` instead.

3. What is the distribution of congressmen across generations?

As expected, Baby boomers dominate the politics of the United States in 2023. However, Generation X is not that far behind. What truly is surprising is the number of Silent Generation members still around in Congress. It is surely safe to say that this generations positions will be filled with Gen Z and Millenials as the decade progresses.

4. Which states have the most congressmen over 65?

Unsurprisingly, Californina and Texas, the most populous states, are also the worst offenders when it comes to having older people run the country. After these two giants, the number quickly declines with the rest of the top 10 having less than 10 older representatives. New Mexico is the only state that has no congressmen over 65.

5. Does the Senate or the House have more elderly?

Starting off with the House, we can see that only around 30% of its members are over 65. This does not seem like too much.

However, things are far more different for the Senate. 50% of the Senate is aged 65 or over! The Senate, is 20% older than the House!

6. Which Congressmen have been in office for the longest?

Perhaps, proving the necessity for term limits, all of the top congressmen in terms of years served have been in office for more than 20 years. The longest serving have been in office nearly as long as the youngest member of the congress has been alive!

Code used

#Data from fivethirtyeight.com
library(tidyverse)
library(usmap)
library(flexdashboard)
#Reading in the data
data <- read_csv("data_aging_congress.csv")
#Basic viewing
head(data)
colnames(data)
View(data)

#Isolating the current congress
geezers <- data %>% 
  filter(congress == 118) %>% 
  select(-congress) 
#Making the party names readable
geezers$party_code[geezers$party_code == 328] <- "Independent" 
geezers$party_code[geezers$party_code == 200] <- "Republican"
geezers$party_code[geezers$party_code == 100] <- "Democrat"

View(geezers)
#Who are the oldest congressmen
oldestGeezers <- geezers %>% 
  arrange(desc(age_years)) %>% 
  select(bioname, age_years, generation, party_code, chamber, state_abbrev, cmltv_cong, cmltv_chamber) %>% 
  rename(Name = bioname) %>% 
  rename(region = state_abbrev)
oldestGeezers$age_years <- round(oldestGeezers$age_years)
oldestGeezers$region <- state.name[sapply(oldestGeezers$region, \(x) which(x == state.abb)[1])]
oldestGeezers$region <- tolower(oldestGeezers$region)
#Graphing out who the oldest congressmen are
ancientGraph <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(age_years > 81) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Name, age_years, fill = party_code, label = age_years)) + geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightblue", "red")) +
  theme(axis.text = element_text(angle = 45)) + geom_text(nudge_y = 1) + 
  ggtitle("Oldest Congressmen, years rounded")
ancientGraph

#Which party has the oldest congressmen
oldestPartyGraph <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(age_years > 65) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(party_code, , fill = party_code)) + geom_bar() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightblue", "yellow", "red")) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ..count..), stat = "count", vjust = 1.5, nudge_y = 5) +
  ggtitle("Parties by members over 65")
oldestPartyGraph

#States map of which states have a large number of Geezer congressmen
#First we need to find out which states have the most geezers
geezerStates <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(age_years > 65) %>% 
  count(region) %>% 
  rename(Quantity = n) %>% 
  rename(state = region)
#Now we merge it with the map data of US states
geezerLand <- plot_usmap(data = geezerStates, values = "Quantity") +
  ggtitle("State by no. of Congressmen over 65")

geezerLand
#Which generation has the most congressmen
geezerGenerationGraph <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  ggplot(aes(generation, fill = generation)) + geom_bar() + 
  geom_text(aes(label = ..count..), stat = "count", vjust = 1.5, nudge_y = 5) + 
  ggtitle("Generations by number of congressmen")
geezerGenerationGraph

#Which congressmen have had the longest time in congress
wontLeaveGraph <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(cmltv_cong > 20) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Name, cmltv_cong, fill = party_code, label = cmltv_cong)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightblue", "red")) +
  geom_col() + theme(axis.text = element_text(angle = 45)) + 
  geom_text() + ggtitle("Longest serving congressmen")

wontLeaveGraph

#Is the Senate or the house older?
#First lets find the percent of elderly in each
totalHouse <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(chamber == "House") %>% 
  count(chamber)
oldHouse <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(chamber == "House") %>% 
  filter(age_years > 65) %>% 
  count(chamber)

housePercent <- oldHouse$n / totalHouse$n

houseGauge <- gauge(housePercent, 0, 1, label = "Percent over 65 in House")
houseGauge

totalSenate <-oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(chamber == "Senate") %>% 
  count(chamber)
oldSenate <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(chamber == "Senate") %>% 
  filter(age_years > 65) %>% 
  count(chamber)

senatePercent <- oldSenate$n / totalSenate$n

senGauge <- gauge(senatePercent, min = 0, max = 1, label = "Percent over 65 in Senate")
senGauge

#Which party is older in the senate
senParties <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(chamber == "Senate") %>% 
  filter(age_years > 65) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(party_code, fill = party_code)) + geom_bar() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightblue", "yellow", "red")) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ..count..), stat = "count", vjust = 1.5, nudge_y = 5) +
  ggtitle("Senators over 65 in the Senate")
senParties

#Which party is older in the House
houseParties <- oldestGeezers %>% 
  filter(chamber == "House") %>% 
  filter(age_years > 65) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(party_code, fill = party_code)) + geom_bar() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightblue", "red")) +
  geom_text(aes(label = ..count..), stat = "count", vjust = 1.5, nudge_y = 5) +
  ggtitle("Representatives over 65")
houseParties
